Its core functions include advocating for the interests of its members, professional supervision, conducting quality control procedures, administering the Wirtschaftsprüfungsexamen (auditing exam), and maintaining the Berufsregister (professional register). The WPK's activities encompass various areas such as quality control, legal frameworks, and the registration of auditors. It offers resources and information on topics like sustainability, digitalization, and regulatory requirements, including the Corporate Sustainability Reporting Directive (CSRD) and EU Taxonomy Regulation. The WPK also provides a Digitalisierungskompass (digitalization compass) to guide members in adopting digital strategies and technologies. Additionally, the WPK facilitates job and cooperation exchanges through its WPK Börsen platform and publishes the WPK Magazin, a member magazine covering legal developments and industry news. The organization also oversees the Aufgaben- und Widerspruchskommission (Tasks and Appeals Committee) which is responsible for the auditing exam. The WPK further supports the professional development of its members through Aus- und Fortbildungsveranstaltungen (training and further education events), including specialized training for quality control auditors. The Kommission für Qualitätskontrolle (Commission for Quality Control) plays a key role in ensuring the quality of audits conducted by its members.
